### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

common

### Is this a regression?

No. It is an incomplete fix: the length guard added in #69000 does not cover non-string inputs.

### Description

#69000 added `assertValidDateFormatLength` to stop the `formatDate` / `DatePipe` DoS (CVE-2026-54268) by rejecting date formats longer than 256 characters. The check reads `format.length`.

`format` is typed `string`, but that is not enforced at runtime. When a non-string value reaches `formatDate`, for example an array Angular's router builds from a repeated query parameter (`?format=a&format=b` yields `['a', 'b']`), `.length` is the element count, not the character count. `['y'.repeat(300)].length` is `1`, so `1 > 256` is false, the guard passes, and the full 300-character string is handed to the same `DATE_FORMATS_SPLIT` loop the guard was meant to protect. The denial of service is reachable again on patched versions.

### Please provide a link to a minimal reproduction of the bug

Minimal Node reproduction (no StackBlitz needed):

```
npm init -y && npm pkg set type=module
npm i @angular/common@22.0.1 @angular/core@22.0.1 @angular/compiler@22.0.1 rxjs zone.js
# save the script below as repro.mjs, then:
node repro.mjs
```

```js
// @angular/compiler is imported only so @angular/common can load in a bare Node script.
import '@angular/compiler';
import { formatDate } from '@angular/common';

const now = new Date();

// 1) A long format STRING is correctly rejected by the length guard added in 22.0.1:
try {
  formatDate(now, 'y'.repeat(300), 'en-US');
  console.log('string : NOT blocked');
} catch (e) {
  console.log('string :', e.message);
}

// 2) The SAME characters as an array bypass the guard, because it checks
//    format.length (the element count, 1) instead of the character count:
const out = formatDate(now, ['y'.repeat(300)], 'en-US');
console.log('array  : NOT blocked, formatDate processed', out.length, 'characters');
```

### Please provide the exception or error you saw

Output on `@angular/common@22.0.1` (Node 25.6). The string form is blocked; the array form is not:

```
string : NG02300: Date format is too long. Exceeded maximum length of 256 characters.
array  : NOT blocked, formatDate processed 300 characters
```

Expected: the array form is rejected the same way the string form is.

